Data Importing, Cleaning and Processing¶

After importing the data and adding in column names and ensuring the numerical data was imported as the correct type, the data cleaning stages occured. The first step was to remove any columns that already appeared to be uniformative. There were six different columsn dropped: the compeititon reference, the application number, the CRN number (compeititon reference number), the competition title, the postcode and the address LEP (local enterprise partnership) of the project. They were dropped because they were either unique number identifiers used by Innovate UK (competition reference, application number, CRN), they contained too granular information that is also captured in another column (postcode and address LEP's information is captured in the address region column) or they contained duplicate information (comeptition title holds the same information as programme title).

Handling Missing Values¶

The first missing value column to deal with was the ISCF, or industrial strategy fund challenge, column. The values in this column were either blank or 'yes', indicating that the column contains information on if the project is apart of the fund or not. I decided to fill each of the null values with 'no', as this would mean they were not in the fund, providing informative information for analysis and ensuring there were no missing values left in the column.

Next, I noticed that there was around the same amount of values were missing from the start date, end date, grant offered, total cost, and actual spend columns. I thought this might be because the missing values all came from the same rows, or projects. To determine this, I subsetted the data to only have the rows where the grant offered column value was null. I then got the sum of the null values in each column in this subset and compared them to the number of missing values from the full data-set. These numbers overlapped, except 1 more innovate uk type was missing and 5 more total cost values.

As 1,359 rows have 7 column values missing, and they only make up 4% of my data-set, I decided it was better to remove them entirely then attempt any imputation, as there is not a clear-cut way to input these values (as most are categorical) and doing it too many times leads to a high risk of changing my final results. Therefore, I removed all rows with a missing value. This resulted in loss of a total of 1,365 data-points which is 4.16% of the data. The resulting data-set has 31,443 rows.

Investigating the dependent variable: Grant Offered¶

My first qustion to answer is what are the biggest determinants of a project’s grant value offered by Innovate UK based on its application, and can we predict how much money a project will receive based on its application? To do this I need to understand the hidden structure behind the grant offered values and make sure that they are fit for modeling and analysis.

Initial Investigation and Descriptive Statistics¶

First, I printed the counts of each of the different values in the grant offered column. This showed a wide-spread and sparsity, with many counts equal to 1. I also noticed that there were 1,721 0 valued grants. While the grants included in the dataset were successfully accepted, the actual grant value amount for funding was still up for consideration. These zero-valued entries could be because the grants eventually did not recieve any money from Innovate UK. I decided to remove these 0-valued grant projects as I want to investigate applications which have been provided with money. Removal will also ensure a smoother data analysis flow as many transformations and modeling algorithms do not handle zero-values well. I have subsetted these 0-valued grants into another dataframe however as they could be useful for comparison further in the analysis. The removal of these 1,721 rows reduced the data-set by 5.47%, leaving a 29,722 row long data-frame

Once I removed the zero-values I calculated some descriptive statistics of the grant offered values to see what is the range of values and quanitiles I will be modeling on. I also plotted a histogram to visualize the frequency of each value and a boxplot to visualize the quantiles more clearly.

Log Normalising the Grant Offered Values¶

The histogram aboves shows a very left skewed distribution and the boxplot shows a very squished IQR with lots of upper value outliers. Due to the left skew in the distribution, I decided to apply a log transformation to the Grant Offered column values. I used qq-plots to visualize and check the transformation and then reploted the histogram and box plot using the log-normal grant-values. I also log-normalized the total cost column and the actual spend column to keep these values comparable during the analysis. I did the transformations as new columns in the dataset to allow me to access the non-transformed data if needed.

GrantOffered Outlier Detection¶

I noticed that in the log-transformed boxplot there was still a lot of outliers both above the IQR upper bound and below the IQR lower bound. To investigate this further, I ploted the normalised grant offered values against the normalised total cost values as well as against sector. In both these plots I also saw values which looked like outliers. It is best to remove outliers as it will help make my predictive model stronger as the pattern in the grant offered values will not be diluted by the outliers. To detect the outliers I used the log-normalized grant offered values as it will reduce the amount of outliers found (as well as ensure the distribution is maintained) as the raw grant offered boxplot is outliers only.

I investigated three different cut-off values for detecting outliers. The first was finding points whose abolute value difference from the mean were twice the standard deviation. The second was finding points whose abolute value difference from the mean were three times the standard deviation. The third was finding values which were within 1.5 times the first quartile and the third quartile of the data. To visualize which points were marked as outliers I used a scatter plot of normalised total cost and grant values and then colored the rows marked as outliers in orange and the normal values as grey.

I decided to use the third method, or the IQR method, as it uses more 'robust' statistics than standard deviation and will help to centralize and reduce my dataset without removing the interesting information or removing too many data-points.

#calculate the mean and standard deviation of the normalised grants to be used to identify outliers
meanGrantNormalised = grants['NormalisedGrants'].mean()
sdGrantNormalised = grants['NormalisedGrants'].std()

#Make a new column in the grants dataframe which labels the row as an outlier or not using the FIRST technique 
#which says an outlier is a value whose absolute difference from the mean is larger than twice the standard deviation
#Outliers are marked as 1 and non-outliers are marked as zero
grants['Outlier1'] = np.where(abs(grants['NormalisedGrants'] - meanGrantNormalised) > 2 * sdGrantNormalised, 1,0)

#Calculate how many datapoints are outliers (1) and non-outliers (0)

#Do the same steps as above but make a column to mark the outliers based on the THIRD technique, or the IQR method
#which labels values as outliers when they are either 1.5 times the IQR below the first quartile 
#or 1.5 time the IQR above the third quartile

#calculate the 1st and third quartile 
quartile_1, quartile_3 = np.percentile(grants['NormalisedGrants'], [25, 75])
#calculate the iqr
iqr = quartile_3 - quartile_1
#calculate the lower and upper bounds of the value range 
lower_bound = quartile_1 - (iqr * 1.5)
upper_bound = quartile_3 + (iqr * 1.5)

#create a new column which labels the rows as either outlier (1) or not (0) based on the IQR method 
grants['Outlier3'] = np.where((grants['NormalisedGrants']> upper_bound) | (grants['NormalisedGrants'] < lower_bound), 1,0)

#See how many outliers and non-outliers there are based on technique 3 
#there is an increase of 274 outliers found by method 3 vs method 2 (422 vs 148) 
#but there is still a large reduction compared to method 1

Feature Engineering: Binning Grant Offered¶

As the raw grant values have a very wide range and have many values with 1 count, I decided to do some binning of them to make classes that will be more informative for a machine learning algorithm. This then means that the machine learning algoirthm I will use will be a classifier. The first bin has an incrament of 5,000 as it is the most popular value, and then each bin goes up by £10,000 up to £185,000 pounds, where it goes up to by £15,000 and then £100,000 up to £400,000. I go up to £400,000 pounds because the third quartile boundary is £308,178 and therefore any new bins above this value will become too small causing a class imablance. In the end there were 23 classes created. There is some class balance still however, as the largest class (£1-5,000) has a little over 10 times the amount of data-points as the smallest class (£175000 - 185000).

Project Number: Duplicated Items¶

There are 14,172 items with a duplicated project number. This means that 45% of submissions are for the same project type. This happens because each partner in the project can submit for their own pot of money.

For example, project number 400229 is about building a new low cost battery system and has 8 submissions for grants by 8 different participants. All other information is the same about the project except for information related to the partners and the 'Grant Offered'. It is important to note this because it means that the amount of money a project recieves is dependent on other variables besides the topic and comeptition it applies to.

Feature Engineering¶

Beside the bined grant value column, two other new features based on the provided columns were generated. The first was the duration of the project in years, to make the dates into it a variable that could be used in a machine learning algorithm. This was created by subtracting the end date year from the start date year. Some projects were only a few months long and thus a zero value because they do not run for a full year.

The second was the ratio of grant offered to total cost, which was calculated by dividing a project's grant offered value by its total cost. This column was generated because my hypothesis is that the total cost of the project is the largest determinate for the amount of grant money a project is given. Analyzing the descriptive statistics of the grant ratios let me see that a ratio of one, meaning that the cost and grant offered are equal, is the most common ratio value and makes up 25% of the value counts (as it is in the third quantile). This can also be visualized in how the histogram distributions of grant value and total cost mirror each other and in a color coded scatter plot of cost vs grant value which is colored by the grant ratio. This insight indicates that total cost may be the largest factor in predicting grant offered values. The ratio could also be used to verify and evalidate any predicted grant offered values generated by a machine learner.

Random Forest: predicting grant bin¶

After data cleaning and feature engineering, the resulting dataframe contained 29,300 rows with 21 feature columns. Only 8 of these columns contained numerical data while the rest contained cateorgical data. To solve the analytical task of predicting the amount of grant money a project will recieve, a random forest classification algorithm was used to predict the classes in the "Grant Bins" column. The randomForest package in R can generate random forests using cateogrical data without the need for one-hot-encoding. This removes the tedious step of creating dummy variables from my workflow and should help to improve the accuracy of my model as any structures in the cateogrical data will not be diluted and the categorical features will not be given a lesser importance than any continuous variabels due to the resulting sparsity of one-hot-encoding (Dingwall and Potts, 2018)). The 'important features' table that Random Forests produce was another reason the algorithm is used as it allows for the easy identification of which variables, and even which levels within those categorical variables, are most important in prediction.

The training and testing of the Random Forest model can be found at https://smcse.city.ac.uk/student/aczh498/inm430/Grant_Prediction_R.html which shows a jupyter notebook which runs on an R kernel.

Investigating the Most Important Features.¶

The variabels of importance plot generated by a random forest ranks which factors are the most important, but it does not tell you how these features affect the outcome. To investigate the exact impact of the most important feature, total cost, a simple linear regression model was created. Then, to investigate the effects of the top three features, a multi-variable linear regression was calculated using total cost, proejct duration in years and enterprise size.

Linear Regression on Total Cost¶

The linear regression showes that for every £1 that the project's cost goes up, the resulting grant value increases by £0.90. The very high R-squared value (0.95) and low standard error (0.0016) shows that the linear regression model fits the data almost perfectly and is very accurate.

Correlation between total cost and grant offered¶

Before generating the regression model, a Pearson and Spearman correlation test was generated to see how strong the relationship is between the grant offered and total cost value of a project. The scatterplot of these two variables, seen in the outlier detection section, shows that most of the data follows a linear relationship. Therefore, a Pearson correlation test should be the correct analysis measure needed, however I calculated both to ensure a hollistic analysis was conducted.

The Pearson correlation value was 0.96 with a p-value of 0.0 and the Spearman correlation value was 0.95 with a p-value of 0.0. As suspected the Pearson was able to capture the relationship, and even generate a higher correlation value, then the Spearman correlation test due to the strong linearity of the data. A zero p-value is due to rounding but it indicates that the correlation has a strong statistical significance.

Further analysis of other features¶

To see the relationship of the other features used in the random forest model, stacked percentage barcharts were generated of the proportion of each feature's levels within a grant bin class. Across the different features the proportions are pretty consistent between the different grant bin classes. This is probably why they contribute such a small amount to the random forest classification model because there is not much variance to distinguish the features between classes. The exception to this is the first grant bin class tends to have a different pattern, but this is probably due to the high amount of samples in this class. One important trend to note is that the Innovate UK product type 'Innovate Vouchers' are only present in the first class (and make up most of it proportionally) because Innovate Vouchers are small grants of £5000 given to small firms to seek expert advice on a project, which is a project classified in the 'emerging and enabling' sector. The graphs below were created in Tableau.

Linear Regression Prediction of Grant Offered Value¶

As the two linear regression models generated showed that the total cost of the project to be the biggest determiner of the grant offered value, I created a linear regression prediction model to test its accuracy and used cross-validation to validate it and make the model more robust. The cross-validation results are very consistent, highlighting how dependent grant value is on cost.

Lastly, I used the model created to predict the grant value offered to the projects which are in the grant_zero data-subset as they had cost figures but no grant offered value.

#train a 10-fold cross validation linear regression model

numberOfSamples = len(grant)
kf = cross_validation.KFold(numberOfSamples, n_folds=10)
foldCount = 0

for train_index, test_index in kf:
    print("-------- We are having the run: ", foldCount )
    arraySubset1 = cost[train_index]
    arraySubset2 = grant[train_index]
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(arraySubset1, arraySubset2)
    
    print ("Slope: ", slope, "Intercept: ", intercept, "r_value: ", r_value, "p_value: ", p_value,"std_err: ", std_err)
    
    xp = np.linspace(arr1.min(), arr1.max(), 100)
    evaluatedLine = np.polyval([slope, intercept], xp)
    # let's see a black line overlaid on the data
    # for each run, we draw a line again
    plt.plot(xp, evaluatedLine, 'k--', linewidth = 1, alpha = 0.3)
    foldCount += 1

#Now, test the accuracy of the model on unseen data 
#by spliting the dataset into a training and testing set 
#and then printing the mean difference betweeen the estimate and the real value

#as well using the arrays generated in the first linear regression model

for train_index, test_index in kf:
    print("-------- We are having the run: ", foldCount )
    arraySubset1 = cost[train_index]
    arraySubset2 = grant[train_index]
    
    unseenSubset1 = cost[test_index]
    unseenSubset2 = grant[test_index]
    
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(arraySubset1, arraySubset2)
    
    # Use the regression models to estimate the unseen grant offered value given the total cost value
    estimatedValues = slope * unseenSubset1 + intercept
    
    # check the difference between the estimates and the real values    
    differences = unseenSubset2 - estimatedValues
    print ('Difference:', np.average(differences))
    print ('UnNormalised Difference (£):', np.exp(np.average(differences)))
    print('R-squared:', r_value)
    foldCount += 1

Investigating Project Titles¶

Before we can analyze the project titles, they need to under go some data processing. The first is spliting the titles by space into a list of words. The first insight I looked into was the value counts for the amount of words in a title. Most projects have only 7 words, with 8 and 6 words being in second and third place. The final edited titles were edited to be all lower case, have puncuation removed, have stop words removed, and any numbers removed.

Word frequency lists and word clouds were then generated on all the project titles and then the project titles split by sector.

#Create a new column which will contain the edited versions of the project titles 
grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'] = grants_wo_outliers['ProjectTitle']

## Processing of the project titles to make them useful for analysis 

#Step 1: make all the words lower case 
grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'] = grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x.lower() for x in x.split()))

#Step 2: remove puncuation from the titles
grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'] = grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'].str.replace('[^\w\s]','')

#step 3: remove numbers 
from string import digits
remove_digits = str.maketrans('', '', digits)
grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'] = grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'].str.translate(remove_digits)

#Step 4: remove stop words
grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'] = grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x for x in x.split() if x not in stop))

#see changes
print(grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited'].head())
print('\n') 

#Print the 20 most frequently used words in the edited project titles
print("20 most used words:\n", pd.Series(' '.join(grants_wo_outliers['TitleEdited']).split()).value_counts()[:20])
